Self-study programs allow learning without having a teacher present,<ref>{{cite web|title=Studying a Language on Your Own |url=http://www.clas.ufl.edu/llc/selfstudy.shtml |publisher=University of Florida |accessdate=13 Sep 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Self-Study: Tell Me More |url=http://www.rug.nl/science-and-society/language-centre/language-courses-and-communication-training/online-language-learning-self-study/?lang=en |publisher=University of Groningen |accessdate=13 Sep 2013}}</ref> and the courses can supplement or replace classroom instruction.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Self-Study Centers at the TUM |url=http://www.sprachenzentrum.tum.de/en/self-study-center/ |publisher=Technical University of Munich |accessdate=13 Sep 2013}}</ref> Universities use self-study programs for less-commonly taught languages, where having professors is not feasible.<ref>{{cite web|title=Self-Directed Language Acquisition Program |url=http://globalstudio.richmond.edu/in-person-services/sdlap.html |publisher=University of Richmond |accessdate=13 Sep 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Directed Independent Language Study |url=http://www.du.edu/ahss/cwlc/language_programs/dils.html |publisher=University of Denver |accessdate=13 Sep 2013}}</ref> Self-study programs are available on paper, audio files, video files, computers, or any combination.<ref>{{cite web|title= Self-study ideas for students learning German for the first time |url=http://www.lsa.umich.edu/german/hmr/lernstrategien/allein_anfangen.html |publisher=University of Michigan |accessdate=13 Sep 2013}}</ref>
This list is limited to programs which teach four or more languages. There are many others which teach one language.
'''Alphabetical Lists of Languages''' show the courses available to learn each language, at Lang1234, Martindale, Omniglot, Rüdiger Köppe, and UCLA. For the thousands of languages not listed on those sites, for which no course exists, [[Global Recordings Network]] has recorded a standard set of Bible stories in 6,000 languages. With effort, learners can study any language by comparing its recordings to the same story in a language they know.<ref>{{cite web|title=Geographic Language Museum|url=http://foreignlanguageexpertise.com/museum2.html|publisher=[[Alexander Argüelles]] |accessdate=2018-02-26}}</ref>
